          "body": "Verse 3 is one of the most exegetically contested verses in the Pentateuch: 'I appeared to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob as God Almighty, but by My name, LORD, I did not make Myself known to them.' The difficulty is that the patriarchs clearly *used* the name YHWH (Genesis 15:2, 7; 28:16). The resolution lies in the verb *yada* — experiential, relational knowing. The patriarchs knew the name YHWH as a title; they did not know it as a *redemptive experience*. The covenant was made under El Shaddai — the God of mountains and abundance. Israel will know YHWH — the God of promise, history, and rescue — through the exodus events themselves. The name is not new information; it is about to become new *experience*. This is progressive revelation: the same God, the same covenant, but a new dimension of knowing opened by new acts in history. Calvin observes that God accommodates His self-disclosure to the redemptive stage the people are in — the patriarchal revelation was sufficient for the patriarchal situation; the exodus revelation is sufficient for the exodus situation."
