          "body": "The seven verbs of vv. 6-8 are the theological center of the entire chapter and arguably the clearest pre-Sinai articulation of YHWH's redemptive purpose in the Old Testament. They move in a sequence that theologians of later centuries will recognize as the gospel's own logic: liberation from bondage (bring out / deliver) → substitutionary rescue (redeem with great judgments) → covenant adoption (take you / be your God) → inheritance (bring in / give the land). The central term is *gaal* — to redeem as a kinsman-redeemer. In Leviticus 25, the *goel* is the nearest male relative who buys back an enslaved kinsman. YHWH claims that role here, declaring Himself Israel's nearest kin. The New Testament writers will reach for this same vocabulary for Christ's atoning work: Galatians 3:13 (Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law), Titus 2:14 (who gave Himself to redeem us), 1 Peter 1:18-19 (redeemed... with the precious blood of Christ). Exodus 6:6 is the root from which that redemption-vocabulary grows."
